<text>Archimedes&apos; Principle of Buoyancy

Archimedes&apos; Principle states that the buoyant force is equal to the weight of the displaced fluid. This principle, discovered by the ancient Greek, can be proven with the following simulation. (Note that the particles in this simulation should be best viewed as some fluid elements, instead of atoms.)

 
The ratio of the mass of the white particles vs. that of the blue ones:
      
(for an interactive simulation of diving and surfacing, click here.)
 
How does buoyancy work?

In this particle model, the buoyant force is undoubtedly due to the fact that the pressure on the ring is lower from the upper side than that from the lower side. As we know, pressure depends not only on the frequency of collisions but also on the mean impulse of each collision. We will leave this question for you to investigate through the simulations.
 


Making this model: This script is used to create the ring structure.

